div.p:
Narrower bounds will ſerue our turne: We ſpeake of Iuſtice firſt as a ſingle vertue. Habits are diſtinguiſhed by their acts; acts by their obiects. The obiect of all morall vertue is good, as of all intellectuall, is True. The obiect of this vertue of Iuſtice is the good of men in relation to each other; Other vertues order a man in regard to himſelfe;
Iuſtice, in regard to another. This good being either common, or priuate; common of all, priuate of ſome; the acts and vertue of Iuſtice muſt bee ſutable; Either, as man ſtands in an habitude to the whole body; or as he ſtands to ſpeciall limbs of the body: The former of theſe is that which Philoſophers and Caſuiſts call a legall and vniuerſall Iuſtice. The latter is that particular Iuſtice, which we vſe to diſtinguiſh by Diſtribution, and Commutation; the one conſiſting in matter of Commerce, the other in Reward, or Puniſhment; both of them according to a meet, though different, equality: An Arithmeticall equality in Commutation; a Geometricall in diſtribution; the former regarding the value, or worth of the thing,
the latter, regarding the proportionable difference of the perſon. The worke of all theſe three Iuſtices, is Peace.
